The unemployment rate is downward trend since it has peaked in April of 2020. If one simply linearly projects the current trend into the rest of 2021 then one gets to unemployment rate of around 5%. The current Federal programs will help and support this trend. However I think the pace of the decline in the unemployment rate will slow down as the labour participation rates will go up as the US economy improves. For instance, under normal economic conditions it took the US economy 12 months between September 2014 and 2015 to get from 6% to 5% unemployment rate and then for further 12 months or so it stayed around 5% before resuming the decrease towards 4%.

A rise or fall of just 0.1 percentage point in the rate translates roughly to 160,000 people, which is equivalent to the population of a medium-sized U.S. city, so that would suggest over 600,000 people were no longer unemployed.

Using previous recoveries and their respective U3 decline speeds as base rate: Last 3 months - 4.9% Last 4 months - 3.7% 2011 pace - 5.8% (chosen as recovery from financial crisis had started in earnest) Apr 14 to Apr 15 pace - 5.8% (chosen as ongoing recovery and starting point of 6.2% is close to where we are now).
Unemployment Rate in the United States averaged 5.77 percent from 1948 until 2021, reaching an all time high of 14.80 percent in April of 2020 and a record low of 2.50 percent in May of 1953.

The Unemployment Rate will move relatively slowly towards lower unemployment. Looking at the past unemployment rates such as those after the GFC, show that it typically returns to "normal levels" gradually.

Obviously the lockdowns have had a tremendous effect on unemployment by forcing businesses to close. So as the lockdowns are lifted over the next few months it would seem reasonable that unemployment would fall.

I predict that the vaccine rollout will continue to hamper people from "returning to normal" by the end of August though I do see more people breaking outside their bubble this summer. While I think covid-19 will have reduced cases in the summer, I don't believe the country will return to "normal" in 2021. I think people are still concerned about the virus and the various strains. Vaccine efficacy has been shown to decrease with the South African variant.

For the past 3 months, unemployment has decreased at a rate of about 0.2% per month. In comparison, after the GFC, when unemployment rates were around where we are now, they decreased by 0.8-1.2% in 12 months, or about half the current speed (of course, the situations are very different). With January at 6.3%, we would expect 4.9% in August if recovery continues the rate it's at now. Assuming a slower recovery similar to post-GFC, that puts us at 5.6%. With vaccinations rapidly increasing, it seems like recovery might speed up as lockdowns are lifted. However, there is no chance of things going back to business as usual as businesses have shuttered, the potential of extra unemployment benefits possibly lasting until fall, and permanent changes to how work is conducted.

The unemployment rate is likely to continue to fall by summer as the effects of covid subside due to the vaccine rollout and more businesses (especially restaurants and travel related businesses) open. This is likely to be sped up by increased stimulus. However, there might be limit to the number of people going back to work immediately, as some have moved, or have adjusted to being out of work for the meantime. This could mean the rate could stay inflated for much mid to late 2021. Because the rate is right now at 6.3%, I see it falling, very likely below 5.9% by August, but probably not below 5.4%.

Personally, I don't see the economy coming back as quickly as most people do. The restaurant, hotel and travel industry are still a long way from resuming their normal trade. And the office building reckoning in the commercial real estate sector has not even begun. Many, many people are MONTHS behind on their rent. And there will be spikes. My two cents.

6.3 currently. But there's a lot of considerations with the pandemic to take into account. The article I linked below gets into it. My understanding is the survey response rates are down due to the pandemic and so it may not be as accurate as normal, among other reasons. Jason Furman estimates in the linked article that the "realistic" unemployment, meaning his estimation of what the employment number would be if the pandemic wasn't screwing up the measurement, is 8.3%. But many of these lost jobs are also temporary and could come back very quickly once the economy opens more. His estimate of the "full recall unemployment rate" is 6.9%. The big question is whether the trend in U3 unemployment reported by the BLS continues and underlying issues with the measure remain the same, or whether these issues resolve and the number better reflects the "realistic" measure. Additionally, if the economy reopens it could reflect the "full recall" number. And of course, all of these numbers are likely to decrease over time.
